Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Reference Research Assistant Regina , SK Description Legislative Library - Reference Research Assistant (On-Site, Full-Time Term – May – August 31, 2024, anticipated) The Legislative Assembly Service of Saskatchewan (LAS) provides the administration and support required for the operation of the Legislative Assembly and provides organizational continuity from one Legislature to the next. The mandate of the Legislative Library is to deliver confidential, non-partisan information services to Members of the Legislative Assembly, develop and maintain the legislative and research collection, and ensure the collection’s present and future accessibility to parliamentarians, the public service, and the people of Saskatchewan. The Saskatchewan Legislative Library invites applications for the position of Reference Research Assistant. Reporting to the Director of Reference Services, the successful candidate will be part of the Reference and Circulation Services team and be responsible for providing research for library products and services. This position also aids with activities in other Library units, as required. The position may be assigned collection development and collection maintenance duties. The Reference Research Assistant undertakes assigned research on a wide range of public policy related topics and synthesizes research information into subject bibliographies, fact sheets, and briefing notes for library information services. Research topics are often multi-faceted, and assignments are subject to tight deadlines. The successful candidate will have superior organizational skills, and the ability to work independently and as a member of a team. As the ideal candidate, you will have knowledge of the principles and practices of library science; the application of library standards and classification systems; current library technology trends; and library reference and research techniques and resources in a parliamentary library environment. You will also have superior information literacy skills and superior written and oral communication skills. Assets would include an understanding of the organization and functions of the legislative branch of government and its relationship with other branches, and an understanding of broad public policy issues. The successful candidate will have completed a 3- or 4-year undergraduate university degree in a social, natural, applied science, or humanities discipline. At least one year of further education in a Master of Library Science (MLS) / Master of Library and Information Studies (MLIS) from an accredited program is also required. All employees of the Legislative Assembly Service are required to provide non-partisan, confidential service to all Members of the Legislative Assembly. To learn more about the LAS, our vision, Mission and Values, and to find further information about the position, salary and benefits, please visit http://www.legassembly.sk.ca/about/employment/.If you are interested in this opportunity, please submit a cover letter and resume, delivered or emailed by 5:00 p.m. (CST) March 22, 2024, to:Director of Reference ServicesAttention: Leslie PolsomRoom 101 - 2405 Legislative Drive,Regina, Saskatchewan S4S 0B3.Tel: (306) 787-1825Email: careers@legassembly.sk.ca Please quote competition 1040218 in the subject of your email.Clearly indicate in your resume or cover letter where and how you have gained the required knowledge and qualifications. Selections for interviews will be based on this information Thank you for your expression of interest. Only candidates selected for interview will be contacted. Compensation $26.038 - $32.630 per hour ($4,062 - $5,090) per month Closes: 22 March, 2024 Saskatchewan Legislative Library Regina , SK Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
