Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Makerspace Specialist Orangeville , ON Description The Corporation of the Town of Orangevilleinvites applications for the position ofMakerspace SpecialistCommunity Services Department, Orangeville Public Library(Full-time position, 35 hours per week) The Orangeville Public Library has an opportunity available for the position of Makerspace Specialist. This position will co-ordinate the delivery of services that are progressive and responsive to customer needs, forming the foundation of an inclusive, active and healthy community. This position investigates, develops, and delivers new technologies which meet the needs of the community in order to develop proficiencies for their professional and personal lives.The Makerspace Specialist is expected to be a strong team player who lives our values to create memorable customer experiences so everyone can reach new heights, creating a collaborative space to engage the community with innovative opportunities for learning, creation, and discovery.Job Duties:Oversees the Library Makerspace, including: Staying abreast of emerging trends and developing a plan to continuously evolve and improve the space with emerging technology, supporting staff with purchasing, and making recommendations for service and equipment improvements in the Makerspace.Installation and configuration of Makerspace software, hardware, and peripheral devices, and maintaining equipment and software. Demonstrating an interest in and ability to use and troubleshoot technology of all kinds while helping patrons in the Makerspace.Maintaining a clean, safe, and welcoming environment for users.Assists patrons in the Makerspace with software and machinery including 3D printers, paper cutting machines, analog-to-digital transfer equipment, digital editing software, camera/videography equipment, etc.; provides direct technical support, training and troubleshooting assistance to staff and the public; and co-ordinates with supervisor to allocate staff resources and meet program needs.Develops, plans, implements, and evaluates programs with a focus on emerging technologies and digital literacy; executes programs responsive to community needs while sparking interest, curiosity, and inspiring patrons to soar to new heights; and develops and runs STEAM themed programs.Provides long and short-term goals to the Digital Transformation Committee; develops and recommends policies for the Makerspace; develops and implements procedures and processes for all Makerspace equipment procedures; produces instructional videos and documentation to ensure safe use; and researches and makes recommendations for technical features, enhancements, or changes to support the betterment of library operations.Seeks, recommends, and completes grant funding/award submissions and program opportunities to enhance current offerings; maintains and keeps current technology inventory database and documents technical issues; collaborates between various Town Divisions or community organizations to provide accessible literacy and community programs.Provides library tours and presentations on library services (school tours, community group visits, community events); and other virtual programming, to be recorded and/or live streamed.Technical support to facilitators, audiences, or partners; and trains, coaches, and directs staff and/or volunteers to achieve objectives.Works collaboratively with Public Services staff to promote library services via social media.Other duties as assigned.Qualifications:University degree specializing in Library Techniques or Community Development; or, a technology, education, library studies, or other relevant field.Three (3) years of work experience facilitating, conducting, co-ordinating programs/meetings.Valid G driver’s license.Demonstrated expertise with current and developing technology trends.Experience delivering technology training, demonstrated interest and competency in technology, digital and analog maker skills, and experience installing and troubleshooting software and hardware.Ability to serve customers effectively and positively in a busy environment, including exercising sound judgment and problem-solving skills, excellent oral and written communication skills that accommodate a diverse population.Demonstrated knowledge of various computer applications, current and emerging library systems, Microsoft Office programs and library eResources (including Libby, Hoopla and LinkedIn Learning).Excellent customer service skills including the ability to run programs and/or facilitate public meetings.The successful candidate will be required to complete a Criminal Record Check, including but not limited to a Vulnerable Sector Check, in accordance with the duties of this position.Salary Range: $76,321.70 to $89,285.59, Band 9 on the Town’s 2024 Pay Grid, plus a comprehensive benefits package Qualified candidates are invited to submit their resumes, in confidence, addressed to Sarah Mayer, Co-ordinator, Human Resources, no later than 4 p.m. on Thursday, March 21, 2024. Applications may be submitted online or submitted in person to the Town Hall located at 87 Broadway. Please do not email your application. To select the best candidates to serve the Town of Orangeville and its people, several screening tools, including Police Record Checks are required as part of the hiring process for some employment or volunteer positions. When requested, applicants are required to provide a Police Record Check as a condition of their offer of employment. Police Record Checks must be dated within three (3) months of the employment offer to be considered valid. The specific type of Police Record Check required will be indicated in the job posting qualifications.The Town of Orangeville is an equal opportunity employer. Accommodations are available for all parts of the recruitment process. Applicants need to make their needs known in advance. By submitting your personal information to the Town of Orangeville, you consent to the collection, use, and disclosure of that information in connection with our recruitment, hiring and/or employment processes. Personal information on this form is collected under the authority of the Municipal Act, 2001, S.O. 2001, c.25, as amended, and will be used to determine the qualifications for employment with the Town of Orangeville. Questions about this collection should be directed to the Manager, Human Resources at 87 Broadway, Orangeville, Ontario L9W 1K1. Compensation $76,321.70 to $89,285.59 Closes: 21 March, 2024 Orangeville Public Library Orangeville , ON Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
